Fun fact, actually in Antarctica we have four players, so they're very active.

54
00:02:48,929 --> 00:02:51,911
So all this means, it leads us to the importance

55
00:02:52,011 --> 00:02:55,573
of storytelling diversity to reach such a global audience.

56
00:02:56,073 --> 00:02:57,253
And when we're talking about diversity,

57
00:02:57,273 --> 00:03:01,276
we're not just talking about diverse characters in game

58
00:03:01,456 --> 00:03:05,398
or diverse ways of dialogue and ways of speaking

59
00:03:05,438 --> 00:03:06,518
to represent those people.

60
00:03:06,838 --> 00:03:08,940
We're talking about diversity of teams

61
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:12,441
that will bring about more authentically diverse stories.

62
00:03:14,197 --> 00:03:18,279
When you have a diverse team, and I'm talking about across demos, we're talking gender,

63
00:03:18,539 --> 00:03:24,661
ethnicity, sexuality, generation, neurotypicality, if that's a word,

64
00:03:25,841 --> 00:03:31,063
all of those sorts of buckets that would make up the diverse human population,

65
00:03:32,103 --> 00:03:37,805
those are the kinds of folks you want to bring to a diverse narrative team. The reason is that

66
00:03:37,865 --> 00:03:42,787
the more folks you have represented at your table in your narrative team, the more perspectives

67
00:03:43,264 --> 00:03:46,387
the more authenticity to those stories and the less fear.

68
00:03:47,519 --> 00:03:50,800
comes less fear and more checks and balances.

69
00:03:50,980 --> 00:03:52,961
So there's no way to represent everybody

70
00:03:54,201 --> 00:03:55,142
within a narrative team.

71
00:03:55,562 --> 00:03:57,362
But when you have more diversity,

72
00:03:57,683 --> 00:03:59,303
you have folks who have more,

73
00:04:00,643 --> 00:04:02,984
they've encountered different stories.

74
00:04:03,024 --> 00:04:04,785
There's more likely to be someone who says,

75
00:04:04,845 --> 00:04:07,066
hey, that sounds like appropriation.

76
00:04:07,126 --> 00:04:08,666
Why don't we go check over here

77
00:04:09,146 --> 00:04:11,607
and get a better feedback

78
00:04:11,667 --> 00:04:13,348
on what the story we're trying to tell.

79
00:04:13,488 --> 00:04:14,508
It makes our stories more authentic.

80
00:04:15,829 --> 00:04:17,929
And when we're talking about diverse stories,

81
00:04:17,949 --> 00:04:20,290
we're talking about dynamically diverse stories.

82
00:04:20,991 --> 00:04:22,591
It's the difference between, you know,

83
00:04:22,631 --> 00:04:23,492
we can research anything.

84
00:04:24,212 --> 00:04:26,833
Google, internet, we can do all of those things, right?

85
00:04:26,873 --> 00:04:28,374
We can come up with a story,

86
00:04:29,794 --> 00:04:33,196
but a personal point of view is much stronger.

87
00:04:33,276 --> 00:04:35,676
It's the difference between hearing about the Civil War

88
00:04:36,077 --> 00:04:38,398
with locations and battles and the dates

89
00:04:38,878 --> 00:04:43,420
versus a soldier's personal on the field remembrances

90
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:45,180
and how engaging that story can be.

91
00:04:46,933 --> 00:04:49,115
And that leads us to specificity.

92
00:04:50,036 --> 00:04:51,878
Specificity leads to universality.

93
00:04:52,278 --> 00:04:53,339
And when I talk about that,

94
00:04:53,439 --> 00:04:55,401
there's two sides to the audience coin.

95
00:04:56,362 --> 00:04:58,504
There is the A side,

96
00:04:58,964 --> 00:05:01,907
the side that's represented on the screen or in the story.

97
00:05:02,327 --> 00:05:04,209
It's familiar to them, it represents them.

98
00:05:05,083 --> 00:05:08,964
themselves or it is familiar to them in some way or it's their story.

99
00:05:09,424 --> 00:05:11,745
The B-side is everyone else, the others.

100
00:05:12,245 --> 00:05:19,067
You're not represented on that screen, but if the representation is authentic, you know,

101
00:05:19,607 --> 00:05:20,487
even if you're the other.

102
00:05:20,867 --> 00:05:25,369
On some subliminal level, even if you can't articulate, you recognize the authenticity,

103
00:05:25,629 --> 00:05:30,950
the truth in that story, in that character, in that plot, the groundedness of the world

104
00:05:31,410 --> 00:05:32,511
and of the interactions.

105
00:05:33,672 --> 00:05:36,813
So when we talk about both sides of that audience coin,

106
00:05:37,313 --> 00:05:39,534
we're talking about a global hunger right now

107
00:05:39,674 --> 00:05:42,234
for diversity in stories and representation.

108
00:05:42,814 --> 00:05:45,955
New stories, new perspectives, perfect examples,

109
00:05:46,195 --> 00:05:48,896
Black Panther, Get Out, Crazy Rich Asians.

110
00:05:49,776 --> 00:05:52,177
Those are all very specific stories

111
00:05:52,297 --> 00:05:54,557
told by very specific personalities,

112
00:05:55,177 --> 00:05:58,578
very specific communities with very specific perspectives.

113
00:05:59,078 --> 00:06:01,659
But global audiences ate those stories up.

114
00:06:02,855 --> 00:06:05,616
regardless if they saw themselves in it

115
00:06:05,916 --> 00:06:07,996
or if they were among the others.

116
00:06:08,916 --> 00:06:10,597
So, and also there's a new,

117
00:06:10,817 --> 00:06:12,297
the new normal is a spectrum

118
00:06:12,657 --> 00:06:14,178
of representation within a story.

119
00:06:14,618 --> 00:06:16,078
Perfect example, Captain Marvel.

120
00:06:16,478 --> 00:06:17,259
So everyone's looking at it,

121
00:06:17,279 --> 00:06:18,619
it's the first female superhero,

122
00:06:18,639 --> 00:06:19,599
but if you've seen the movie,

123
00:06:20,079 --> 00:06:21,420
there are many women.

124
00:06:22,120 --> 00:06:24,961
many diverse people of color mixed in,

125
00:06:25,001 --> 00:06:27,583
and no one's like, hey, here's this other person,

126
00:06:27,623 --> 00:06:29,804
and it's not called attention, attention's not called to it,

127
00:06:30,144 --> 00:06:32,545
but it's strong, and it gives a stronger story,

128
00:06:32,725 --> 00:06:34,566
and an audience that's more engaged.

129
00:06:35,246 --> 00:06:37,567
This hunger leads to audience engagement.

130
00:06:38,087 --> 00:06:40,469
Engaged, happy players equal profit.

131
00:06:40,589 --> 00:06:42,289
That's in case you need a business case

132
00:06:42,410 --> 00:06:46,151
for why diverse staffing is important, there you go.

133
00:06:49,013 --> 00:06:49,133
So.

134
00:06:50,832 --> 00:06:56,764
The whole concept of mentorship as it was kind of

135
00:06:56,784 --> 00:07:00,611
developed on our team.

136
00:07:01,511 --> 00:07:04,353
was basically we were confronted with a problem.

137
00:07:04,513 --> 00:07:06,814
We had, at the beginning of last year,

138
00:07:06,834 --> 00:07:09,816
a couple of vacancies in the narrative department.

139
00:07:09,876 --> 00:07:12,638
We were looking for a couple of writer narrative designers.

140
00:07:13,399 --> 00:07:15,780
And when we opened up the job position

141
00:07:15,820 --> 00:07:17,101
and we started getting applications,

142
00:07:17,141 --> 00:07:19,843
we started realizing that we were

143
00:07:19,863 --> 00:07:22,865
seeing a lot of the same people applying for the job

144
00:07:23,405 --> 00:07:23,925
repeatedly.

145
00:07:24,086 --> 00:07:24,506
That's great.

146
00:07:25,827 --> 00:07:28,390
Just because someone didn't get a job the first time they

147
00:07:28,430 --> 00:07:31,313
applied doesn't mean that they're not qualified.

148
00:07:31,353 --> 00:07:33,816
It might just mean that what we were looking for specifically,

149
00:07:34,517 --> 00:07:37,080
they didn't have, or there was someone more

150
00:07:37,120 --> 00:07:38,001
appropriate for the role.

151
00:07:38,061 --> 00:07:41,245
But we did start realizing that we had a lot of.

152
00:07:42,213 --> 00:07:43,933
the same applicants over and over again,

153
00:07:44,013 --> 00:07:45,874
and we weren't really seeing a lot of new people

154
00:07:45,894 --> 00:07:47,994
come through the pipeline for review.

155
00:07:48,795 --> 00:07:52,576
We also started realizing that after talking to some folks

156
00:07:53,136 --> 00:07:55,756
about the position, we realized that they were interested

157
00:07:55,776 --> 00:07:57,297
in the job, but they didn't bother applying

158
00:07:57,337 --> 00:08:00,978
because when they looked at the job requirements, they...

159
00:08:01,818 --> 00:08:04,600
felt that because they didn't meet every single bullet point

160
00:08:05,481 --> 00:08:07,703
that they would have no chance, and therefore, they

161
00:08:07,723 --> 00:08:08,723
didn't bother applying.

162
00:08:09,264 --> 00:08:12,146
So they were sort of self-selecting themselves out

163
00:08:12,186 --> 00:08:13,047
of the candidate pool.

164
00:08:13,787 --> 00:08:18,811
And also because those job requirements were a bit heavy,

165
00:08:18,871 --> 00:08:21,113
we were asking for people who had experience in television

166
00:08:21,593 --> 00:08:25,837
and then also in other media like comics or novelizations

167
00:08:25,877 --> 00:08:26,537
or pen and paper.

168
00:08:28,887 --> 00:08:30,267
There was a bit of a barrier to entry.

169
00:08:30,387 --> 00:08:33,409
We were getting some people who were applying who had really

170
00:08:33,469 --> 00:08:37,771
great portfolios and samples, but because they lacked the

171
00:08:37,791 --> 00:08:40,552
years on the job that we were looking for, we were actually

172
00:08:40,572 --> 00:08:44,514
hiring for a mid-level position, that they just

173
00:08:45,454 --> 00:08:46,895
decided not to bother.

174
00:08:47,816 --> 00:08:53,478
So these promising candidates, we realized that we were

175
00:08:53,558 --> 00:08:55,939
discouraging them, and we needed to do

176
00:08:56,039 --> 00:08:56,720
something about it.

177
00:08:58,613 --> 00:09:04,039
At the end of the review cycle, we figured, let's take a look at this and figure out if

178
00:09:04,059 --> 00:09:05,040
there's a better way to do it.

179
00:09:06,741 --> 00:09:11,046
So we figured that mentorship might actually be a good solution to the problem.

180
00:09:13,662 --> 00:09:16,946
If we could provide a roadmap to the candidates who

181
00:09:17,647 --> 00:09:20,390
were promising but maybe not quite ready for the job,

182
00:09:20,450 --> 00:09:22,052
we could maybe help prepare them,

183
00:09:22,492 --> 00:09:24,895
not only for a job with us, but really for a job

184
00:09:25,155 --> 00:09:26,577
at any studio in the industry.

185
00:09:27,137 --> 00:09:31,442
We felt that getting more people into the mix

186
00:09:31,682 --> 00:09:34,085
would ultimately benefit the industry as a whole.

187
00:09:35,626 --> 00:09:42,408
We would offer support to those folks and also basically make ourselves available,

188
00:09:42,968 --> 00:09:46,570
whether it was during work hours for certain sessions or

189
00:09:46,690 --> 00:09:49,290
just make ourselves available to answer

190
00:09:49,411 --> 00:09:51,511
e-mails if they had questions about any particular thing.

191
00:09:52,011 --> 00:09:54,552
Lastly, we wanted the mentorship program to be self-directed.

192
00:09:54,972 --> 00:09:57,473
Not everybody coming in was going to be looking for the same thing,

193
00:09:58,093 --> 00:10:02,195
and rather than try and manage every person trying to come through the program,

194
00:10:02,782 --> 00:10:06,385
we felt that it would be better if we put that responsibility

195
00:10:06,485 --> 00:10:06,786
on them.

196
00:10:08,627 --> 00:10:12,130
So now that we decided that we wanted

197
00:10:12,170 --> 00:10:14,492
to use mentorship as a way for people to kind of get

198
00:10:14,552 --> 00:10:16,614
over that hurdle, whether it's to get their first job

199
00:10:16,654 --> 00:10:19,536
or just to kind of leverage their own experiences

200
00:10:19,597 --> 00:10:21,939
into a new career path, we needed

201
00:10:21,999 --> 00:10:24,521
to figure out who we were going to invite to participate.

202
00:10:24,701 --> 00:10:27,583
So we set out a couple of guidelines,

203
00:10:27,603 --> 00:10:28,424
and they were very simple.

204
00:10:28,504 --> 00:10:30,246
We were actually going to open the mentorship

205
00:10:30,266 --> 00:10:31,126
program to anybody.

206
00:10:31,567 --> 00:10:36,911
So anybody could apply or express interest.

207
00:10:37,572 --> 00:10:39,513
But we wanted to also focus on folks

208
00:10:39,553 --> 00:10:41,154
who needed a little bit of extra help getting

209
00:10:41,194 --> 00:10:42,576
over that hurdle for the first job.

210
00:10:43,036 --> 00:10:46,198
So we were looking for people whose voices were

211
00:10:46,258 --> 00:10:48,680
underrepresented in game narrative.

212
00:10:49,361 --> 00:10:51,663
Those who were experiencing financial hardships

213
00:10:51,743 --> 00:10:53,284
didn't have the means to necessarily get

214
00:10:53,324 --> 00:10:56,847
the education that is often required for these jobs.

215
00:10:57,307 --> 00:11:02,112
and folks who show strength of character like veterans and folks involved in public service.

216
00:11:04,013 --> 00:11:09,438
To sort of summarize that, everyone who is, when we say underrepresented voices,

217
00:11:09,578 --> 00:11:16,464
we really mean not white, not male, cis, male, heterosexual, that little bucket.

218
00:11:17,285 --> 00:11:21,088
So investing in those future storytellers

219
00:11:21,168 --> 00:11:22,830
and bringing them to the table is not just

220
00:11:22,870 --> 00:11:24,571
about hiring an arena net like Bobby said,

221
00:11:25,211 --> 00:11:28,374
it's also about elevating the industry as a whole.

222
00:11:28,774 --> 00:11:32,117
The more really strong storytellers we have out there

223
00:11:32,177 --> 00:11:34,278
in games, the better stories we'll have in games,

224
00:11:34,298 --> 00:11:38,462
the more engaged people will be in what we're creating.

225
00:11:41,265 --> 00:11:43,467
So now that we had decided to start the program,

226
00:11:43,507 --> 00:11:44,828
we needed to reach out to folks.

227
00:11:45,468 --> 00:11:47,070
The first thing that we did is actually

228
00:11:47,690 --> 00:11:51,533
get back in touch with folks who had applied for the position

229
00:11:51,573 --> 00:11:53,515
with us, but didn't quite make the cut.

230
00:11:54,015 --> 00:11:56,477
We scheduled conference calls with them,

231
00:11:56,537 --> 00:11:59,279
kind of explained to them why we felt they weren't quite

232
00:11:59,340 --> 00:12:00,581
ready for a job with us.

233
00:12:00,721 --> 00:12:02,942
But we then extended the offer to have

234
00:12:02,962 --> 00:12:04,944
them participate in the mentorship program.

235
00:12:07,326 --> 00:12:09,007
We also polled our professional network.

236
00:12:09,047 --> 00:12:12,370
We started asking narrative folk at other companies

237
00:12:13,271 --> 00:12:16,893
and asking if they knew of anyone through their network

238
00:12:17,494 --> 00:12:18,374
who they could recommend.

239
00:12:19,295 --> 00:12:20,956
Lastly, we reached out on social media.

240
00:12:21,016 --> 00:12:25,600
If there was anybody whose conduct and candor

241
00:12:25,880 --> 00:12:28,082
and thoughts about narrative design and writing

242
00:12:28,682 --> 00:12:30,504
we felt were interesting or promising,

243
00:12:30,524 --> 00:12:33,065
we would reach out to them and try and get to know them

244
00:12:33,106 --> 00:12:33,626
a little bit better.

245
00:12:35,771 --> 00:12:43,796
So I was one of these people who was looking to break into narrative design and writing for games.

246
00:12:43,816 --> 00:12:51,682
A little secret, I'm older than I might look and so when I was in undergrad there weren't

247
00:12:52,022 --> 00:12:56,565
any creative narrative game development tracks.

248
00:12:57,486 --> 00:12:59,589
It just wasn't anything that folks were thinking about.

249
00:12:59,629 --> 00:13:03,635
Like maybe if you were in computer engineering,

250
00:13:04,055 --> 00:13:04,896
it was something for you.

251
00:13:04,997 --> 00:13:06,979
But from a creative writing perspective,

252
00:13:07,340 --> 00:13:09,283
it just wasn't there from a storytelling perspective.

253
00:13:10,184 --> 00:13:10,945
I was a film student.

254
00:13:11,706 --> 00:13:12,607
My first career.

255
00:13:13,128 --> 00:13:18,671
was as a creative producer and writer in variety TV and video.

256
00:13:19,791 --> 00:13:23,173
I had a few years prior to looking to move into games

257
00:13:23,273 --> 00:13:25,854
where I was working as a developing content

