00:13:57,784 --> 00:14:02,628
didn't know because every single studio has a different posting

266
00:14:02,728 --> 00:14:05,371
for what it is to be a writer, a writer narrative designer,

267
00:14:05,631 --> 00:14:06,412
a narrative designer.

268
00:14:06,652 --> 00:14:07,753
Everybody's terms are different.

269
00:14:08,054 --> 00:14:09,735
I couldn't figure out when everybody

270
00:14:09,775 --> 00:14:13,339
says change your resume to reflect this particular job

271
00:14:13,379 --> 00:14:17,403
posting, what in my varied freelance career of

272
00:14:18,544 --> 00:14:23,986
more than decade, could be applied for what I was trying to get into.

273
00:14:25,267 --> 00:14:29,189
Let's be honest, studios and narrative departments and recruiters,

274
00:14:29,229 --> 00:14:33,231
when they're posting something and trying to fill a spot on their team,

275
00:14:33,491 --> 00:14:40,214
they don't have time to walk applicants through how to showcase what your skills are

276
00:14:40,234 --> 00:14:44,396
and how to tell them that you really should be on their team.

277
00:14:44,416 --> 00:14:45,177
So...

278
00:14:47,918 --> 00:14:49,940
I didn't know what I didn't know, right?

279
00:14:50,840 --> 00:14:54,463
I'm a storyteller, but the games industry, that landscape,

280
00:14:55,224 --> 00:14:57,205
was really foreign to me, and I needed a map.

281
00:14:58,386 --> 00:14:59,847
I was doing informational interviews,

282
00:15:00,868 --> 00:15:04,211
but I really wished for the sort of invaluable resource

283
00:15:04,431 --> 00:15:08,334
of hands-on training, field apprenticeship, if you will.

284
00:15:09,114 --> 00:15:12,577
I needed honest feedback and quality attention

285
00:15:13,037 --> 00:15:14,438
from folks who were already in it.

286
00:15:17,538 --> 00:15:22,642
So now that we were committed to doing the program,

287
00:15:22,762 --> 00:15:24,344
and we had actually reached out to folks,

288
00:15:24,484 --> 00:15:27,947
we wanted to actually have a plan of what

289
00:15:27,987 --> 00:15:28,868
to do once they showed up.

290
00:15:29,528 --> 00:15:32,391
So we decided to focus on three major areas

291
00:15:32,431 --> 00:15:35,273
that we felt would be most useful to mentees who

292
00:15:35,293 --> 00:15:35,814
were trying to.

293
00:15:36,967 --> 00:15:41,712
market themselves, but then also to us as a team looking to grow.

294
00:15:43,254 --> 00:15:46,998
Basically, if we could foster somebody's career development,

295
00:15:47,038 --> 00:15:49,862
what would we want to advise them on?

296
00:15:49,922 --> 00:15:52,264
So we've broken into three categories.

297
00:15:52,404 --> 00:15:56,089
Screenwriting, just basically writing screenplays or teleplays

298
00:15:56,109 --> 00:15:57,951
to adapt it for games.

299
00:15:59,012 --> 00:16:02,134
Narrative design, basically getting people to understand

300
00:16:02,175 --> 00:16:05,718
that they are writing not just for linear media,

301
00:16:05,778 --> 00:16:08,340
that we have concepts of things like branching,

302
00:16:08,400 --> 00:16:11,123
that we often will be partnering with game designers

303
00:16:11,203 --> 00:16:16,187
and artists and programmers to represent the story

304
00:16:16,427 --> 00:16:19,330
in outside of scenes and cinematics,

305
00:16:19,410 --> 00:16:20,651
but also through gameplay.

306
00:16:21,460 --> 00:16:23,061
And lastly, career development.

307
00:16:23,161 --> 00:16:26,163
A lot of schools don't really give you much coaching when

308
00:16:26,203 --> 00:16:28,945
it comes to how to be a good collaborative

309
00:16:29,085 --> 00:16:30,866
partner on the job.

310
00:16:32,647 --> 00:16:35,189
So we felt that if there was anything that we could do to

311
00:16:35,849 --> 00:16:40,191
give people tips and a little bit of direction on how to

312
00:16:40,232 --> 00:16:42,533
present themselves in interviews, and also once they

313
00:16:42,553 --> 00:16:46,355
were on the job, how to basically be good partners in

314
00:16:46,735 --> 00:16:47,236
development.

315
00:16:47,816 --> 00:16:51,239
basically to be good advocates for story,

316
00:16:51,279 --> 00:16:55,463
but then also to respect partners in adjacent disciplines.

317
00:16:57,333 --> 00:17:00,994
So the structure was we would meet once per week.

318
00:17:01,055 --> 00:17:03,575
Every Wednesday, the mentees would come in.

319
00:17:04,175 --> 00:17:07,276
We would play the game together for about an hour, at

320
00:17:07,316 --> 00:17:10,177
which point various members of staff would answer any

321
00:17:10,237 --> 00:17:12,998
questions if people were new to the game that we were making.

322
00:17:13,418 --> 00:17:15,719
But then after that session was over, we would spend the

323
00:17:15,759 --> 00:17:18,479
next couple of hours doing a variety of things.

324
00:17:18,539 --> 00:17:21,260
Some days it would be just a question and answer session of

325
00:17:21,280 --> 00:17:21,560
people.

326
00:17:22,201 --> 00:17:24,582
had something that they wanted to learn more about.

327
00:17:25,043 --> 00:17:27,525
We would do lectures or give presentations

328
00:17:27,585 --> 00:17:30,447
on various aspects of screenwriting or narrative design.

329
00:17:31,528 --> 00:17:34,890
We'd also give feedback either on the scripts

330
00:17:34,951 --> 00:17:36,071
that people want to show us

331
00:17:36,372 --> 00:17:38,914
or on some projects that they were working on.

332
00:17:39,674 --> 00:17:42,216
Lastly, we would periodically give assignments.

333
00:17:42,256 --> 00:17:44,038
So at the end of a presentation...

334
00:17:44,838 --> 00:17:47,400
covering a particular topic, we would ask them to come back

335
00:17:47,580 --> 00:17:51,242
for the following week and maybe dissect

336
00:17:52,103 --> 00:17:55,545
a narrative moment or gameplay moment from something that they had been playing

337
00:17:55,905 --> 00:17:59,448
and kind of break it apart into its components and talk about

338
00:17:59,848 --> 00:18:03,530
if they were to re-engineer it or if a game director came to them and said,

339
00:18:03,590 --> 00:18:04,131
okay, listen,

340
00:18:04,331 --> 00:18:07,133
we need to change the sequence. Let's not use a cinematic, but

341
00:18:07,553 --> 00:18:10,515
do this through gameplay. Like, what ideas could they bring to the table?

342
00:18:10,835 --> 00:18:13,717
So that we get them thinking critically about story delivery in games.

343
00:18:15,040 --> 00:18:16,625
beyond just the script itself.

344
00:18:18,715 --> 00:18:23,640
Here's a picture of a couple of mentees and some of the guys

345
00:18:23,660 --> 00:18:26,322
who work at ArenaNet, game designers.

346
00:18:27,283 --> 00:18:31,146
This is really to show it was a very casual environment

347
00:18:31,166 --> 00:18:34,449
a lot of times that fostered that sort of relationship

348
00:18:34,589 --> 00:18:36,371
and give and take and asking questions.

349
00:18:37,852 --> 00:18:42,396
And also just dialogue, which is very important and also very

350
00:18:42,516 --> 00:18:44,178
rare when you're trying to break in.

